data.title: Adam Devine Breaks Down His Most Iconic Characters
data.meta_description: Adam Devine breaks down his most iconic characters, including roles in Mail Order Comedy, Workaholics, Pitch Perfect, Game Over, Man!, Mike and Dave Need Wedding Dates, The Intern, When We First Met, and more.
data.text:
All I can remember is not a great craft service,

which is how I judge every production

and the smell on set was so repugnant,

it felt like a very, very small gym,

but we weren't working out

and I don't know what that smell was.

Hi, I'm Adam Devine and these are my Iconic Characters.

(dynamic upbeat music)

Mail Order Comedy, MOC, baby,

it was like right when YouTube first came out,

we were like, oh, my God, like we can actually post videos

and people will see them

and dozens of people watched our videos every week,

so we thought we were superstars.

An ice cold Sierra Nevada Sausagefest.

Yeah, Sausagefest was, we actually were just having a party

and we had all of our equipment at our house

and we were like there's not a girl here,

we should just have a beer called Sausagefest

and then have the tagline be, Bring on the dudes.

We just filmed our actual party

with not a single girl there, there was one girl

and we were like, sorry, you have to sit this one out.

Workaholics was like our ultimate dream come true.

My character in Workaholics,

I was Adam DeMamp the Champ, full on maniac.

People are always weirded out, when they meet me in person,

because I'm not like that peak level of crazy

and they're like,

Oh, I thought you'd be like much more of a maniac,

I thought you'd be just like DeMamp,

and I'm like, I would be dead,

that man should have died like 30 times

or at least so concussed,

he couldn't put a sentence together.

Oh, my head.

Blake and Ders, I hate them, hate them

as people, as people, I hate them,

as co-stars, great, great guys,

but as human beings, they're monsters.

Season three opener, Business Trip,

Anders gets invited to go on this business trip with Alice,

our boss to close this by account with the Barracuda,

so we sort of tag along, 'cause he's got this suite

and we're gonna party.

Happy Business Trip!

Whoa, how did we beat you here, man,

we got fireworks, pretty cool, right?

Guys, this is a no.

We sort of get found out, that we're there

and Alice comes and she's like,

We've gotta shut this down,

but then the Barracuda's there as well

and she's like, Wait, you guys are doing drugs?

I wanna do it, I'm here to party,

and so then we all take acid

and then it just fully spirals out of control.

Kyle Newacheck, who ended up being our director

for basically everything we've ever done,

that's where he really ran with all the visual stuff

and we kind of let him do what he does,

so like any time that we zone out

and go into like their little drug world,

that's sort of where he kind of stylistically

made it pretty awesome and incredible,

thank God we had him, that show could've really sucked.

Pitch Perfect was, I'm so glad I did that movie,

'cause I was on the fence,

'cause it was right after I did Workaholics.

Luckily the script was super funny.

I asked Blake and Ders,

like what do you guys think of the script,

it's me acapella singing and Ders read it and was like,

It's really funny, I think you'll crush it in this role,

and then Blake was like,

Yeah, yeah, I also think it's good,

and then came in my office like late at night,

when I was working and was like,

Don't do this movie, you're gonna bury us,

no one will like Workaholics,

if you're in a singing movie,

and you're an idiot, Blake, because that movie came out

and it was so funny and people really liked it

and so I'm really glad I did it.

My character, Bumper, a little bit of an egomaniac,

really just wants to be the greatest,

but once again has that level,

that base level of insecurity, that you're like,

oh, this guy's compensating for something.

I did a lot of vocal warmups to prepare for the role,

it was always

♪ Double bubble, triple bubble gum, yum yum ♪

♪ Aluminum, linoleum, aluminum, linoleum ♪

♪ Aluminum, linoleum, yum yum ♪

I did that for three months straight

and then shot the movie.

But we did this riff off in Pitch Perfect,

where on paper, I'm like, hm, how's this gonna play?

But then they shot it all cool,

we're in a pool and there's lights and it's at night

and then it's just us

aggressively like singing to each other,

which sounds really dumb and is really dumb,

but very, very funny.

♪ Let's talk about sex, alright ♪

♪ Let's talk about sex, a little bit, a little bit ♪

Game Over, Man was like our little baby.

It's sort of like Die Hard-esque,

but instead of cool, badass John McClane,

you have three idiots. (laughing)

I play Alexxx with three Xs

and, was that four?

He's like that friend that you have,

that you love him to death,

but you can't invite him over for a chill night,

only the big events does Alexxx with three Xs get invited,

you've gotta keep him clear,

because he's like, We should chug this.

Do you think this would break on my head?

Do you think this would fit on my, what's that?

We had to do this scene,

where we're like strapped in to an ironing board

and we swing across from two buildings

and we shot it on this green screen,

but we're still hanging like 80 feet in the air

and then we're dropped and so all day long,

it was like we're on a very aggressive rollercoaster,

but instead of a like a comfortable rollercoaster seat,

you're like kind of hanging off this clothes hanging board.

This was the coolest shit, coming out of the fucking window,

doing a badass exit,

now we look like a bunch of fucking losers hanging up here.

Very weird bruises, like I'm a dominatrix or something,

'cause I had to wear this harness,

so I had like aggressive bruises right here.

My girlfriend was, you know, trying to like

get a little nooky and I'm like, not now,

this whole zone is off limits.

Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg produced Game Over, Man

and we'd been working on this movie for years

and they were shooting Neighbors, when we first signed up

to have them produce our movie with us and they were like,

Come on down, we'll figure something out for you,

and they had us invent Beer Pong.

I hope in 100 years, that's just history,

like people are going like,

Actually, no, it's in this movie,

the people that invented Beer Pong

are the guys from Workaholics.

They really wanted me to sink a bowl

and it took me like, it took two hours to shoot that scene,

because for 45 minutes, I'm like, I'll get it!

No, just give me another shot!

And they're like, We could just drop it off frame,

and I'm like, no, we're not, we're getting it in one!

I was a real monster about it.

Yeah, Mike and Dave Need Wedding Dates

was like that was the dream gig for me,

I fought like tooth and nail to get it.

I play Mike Stangle, he's the older brother,

but he's the one that doesn't have

his shit together the most

and he's definitely that archetype

that I sort of like find my way in

of like a guy with all this false bravado

with a level of insecurity at its base,

who really just wants things to go his way,

but throughout the movie,

things just start spinning more and more out of control

and by the end, he's full on manic mode.

No!

At the beginning of the movie,

you see all these things going right,

like us jumping on a trampoline

and like I kiss a girl, that's on the roof

and then we're like shooting Roman candles at each other

and it's kind of cute and fun, we're doing like a fun dance

and then cut to the Dad shows us the tape

of what actually happened at all those family functions

and I headbutt the girl and she falls off

and we're both bloody,

we're shooting Roman candles at each other

and we accidentally shoot it inside this camper

and it explodes.

It was fun up to that point.

And I thought that was like a real cool, clever way

to show like how we picture ourselves

and how we actually are.

The Intern was this cool Nancy Meyers movie that I did.

So I played the character, Jason,

I sort of was the head of the interns

and De Niro was one of the new interns at the office

and I kind of showed him the ropes,

but then he showed me how to live life as a real man.

And I assume you talked to her, apologized,

told her how much she means to you?

Well, you know.

You didn't talk to her?

What did you do, send her a Tweet?

No, of course not, I like texted her a billion times.

It was kind of fun for me to play this character,

because he wasn't so broad

as like Bumper was or Adam DeMamp

and I kind of got to play a more grounded character.

Robert De Niro was like, obviously he's like the man, right,

but he's really quiet.

If he thinks you're funny, he likes you

and so luckily he kind of thought I was funny

and like snuck in there,

he wouldn't emit sound, when he would laugh,

he would just jiggle,

which if you've ever seen Robert De Niro just jiggle,

the funniest thing in the world,

'cause he does super De Niro face,

you'll say something funny,

he'll just make the De Niro face and go.

Ratko: The Dictator's Son,

I think they paid us like $11,

it's not one of my proudest moments,

but I'll wear it with a badge of honor.

I think I was like generic party boy number four

and that's basically what I've been playing

the rest of my career.

From what I can remember of that film.

Fiesta!

(Mariachi music)

It doesn't hold up, I'll say that.

When We First Met was this movie I did,

me, Alexandra Daddario, Shelley Hennig,

it sort of starts out, we're at her engagement party

and you think that I'm gonna be the one,

that's going to marry the girl,

it turns out I'm not and I'm depressed

and I like loved her and I've like since been friend zoned

and I go to the place, that we had our first drinks together

and I fall into this photo booth,

where we took photos many years ago

and it's sort of like the Zoltron machine in Big

and I go back in time to see what I can do,

if I could change something when I first met her

and then every time that I do something,

I wake up the next day with those consequences.

It was a really fun character to play,

'cause I got to play a bunch of different,

I got to play like the sweet version of myself,

the maniac version, the douchy version,

the cool guy version and that was mt favorite version,

because I got to be like, like I got to play this guy,

why do cool guys always look like

they have something in their eyes,

have you ever noticed that?

Like they could be totally normal

and then they're like, Hey, what's up?

Let's go to this party,

and then cool guy does like,

What's up?

I feel like my role as Chief Party Officer

for Captain Morgan is maybe

the role I've been destined to play.

Oh, oh, oh, so much more than that.

Every one of my roles have been a stepping stone to be here,

because they've all been fun guy, party animals,

but now I know how to handle myself

and if you party with the Captain,

you've got to be able to handle yourself,

'cause that guy, that guy's knows what's up.

So we went and surprised this dude, Tyler

on his 30th birthday party

and just sort of showed up at his house

and just sort of partied with this guy and his friends

and like I didn't know how it was gonna go,

'cause this was a surprise party and it just blew his mind

and we had like a pretty great time.

Every role is like a little different

and you want to make it unique for that character,

but then I feel like people also want to see

the thing that makes you special as well

come through that character,

so I always try to bring some uniqueness,

keep it grounded on some level,

that every person can go like, I know that guy.

(dynamic upbeat music)
